const e={topicId:"adjective-agreement",title:"Adjective Agreement in Romanian",introduction:"In Romanian, adjectives must agree with the noun they describe in gender (masculine, feminine, neuter) and number (singular, plural). This means most adjectives have up to four forms. Adjectives usually come AFTER the noun, which is the opposite of English word order.",sections:[{id:"how-adjectives-change",title:"How Adjectives Change",blocks:[{type:"rule",title:"Four Forms of an Adjective",content:"Most Romanian adjectives have four forms: masculine singular, feminine singular, masculine plural, and feminine plural. Neuter nouns use the masculine form in singular and the feminine form in plural, so neuter does not require a separate adjective form."},{type:"table",headers:["Form","frumos (beautiful)","mare (big)","bun (good)"],rows:[["Masc. sg.","frumos","mare","bun"],["Fem. sg.","frumoasă","mare","bună"],["Masc. pl.","frumoși","mari","buni"],["Fem. pl.","frumoase","mari","bune"]],caption:"Three adjectives showing all four forms",colorCoded:!0},{type:"callout",variant:"info",content:'Notice that "mare" (big) has fewer changes — it is the same for masculine and feminine singular. Some adjectives, like "mare" and "verde" (green), are simpler because they do not change as much.'}]},{id:"common-patterns",title:"Common Adjective Patterns",blocks:[{type:"text",content:'The most common adjective pattern changes the ending based on gender and number. Here is the typical pattern for adjectives ending in a consonant (like "frumos"):'},{type:"table",headers:["Pattern","Masc. sg.","Fem. sg.","Masc. pl.","Fem. pl."],rows:[["-os / -oasă","frumos","frumoasă","frumoși","frumoase"],["-or / -oare","ușor","ușoară","ușori","ușoare"],["-consonant / -ă","mic","mică","mici","mici"],["-e (invariable sg.)","mare","mare","mari","mari"]],caption:"Common adjective ending patterns"},{type:"example",romanian:"Am o casă frumoasă.",english:"I have a beautiful house.",highlights:[{text:"Am",role:"verb"},{text:"o casă frumoasă",role:"object"}]},{type:"example",romanian:"Băieții sunt frumoși.",english:"The boys are handsome.",highlights:[{text:"Băieții",role:"subject"},{text:"sunt",role:"verb"}]}]},{id:"position-of-adjectives",title:"Position of Adjectives",blocks:[{type:"rule",title:"After the Noun (Usually)",content:'In Romanian, adjectives normally come AFTER the noun: "o casă mare" (a big house), not "o mare casă." Some adjectives can go before the noun for emphasis or in fixed expressions, but the default position is always after.'},{type:"diagram",slots:[{position:1,label:"Article",content:"o",role:"other"},{position:2,label:"Noun",content:"fată",role:"subject"},{position:3,label:"Adjective",content:"frumoasă",role:"other"}],caption:"Default word order: Article + Noun + Adjective"},{type:"comparison",left:{title:"Normal position (after noun)",items:["o casă mare (a big house)","un om bun (a good man)","o zi frumoasă (a beautiful day)"]},right:{title:"Emphatic position (before noun)",items:["frumoasa casă (the beautiful house)","buna dimineața (good morning)","Fixed expressions only"]}},{type:"example",romanian:"Am un câine mic și un pisică mare.",english:"I have a small dog and a big cat.",highlights:[{text:"Am",role:"verb"},{text:"un câine mic",role:"object"},{text:"un pisică mare",role:"object"}]},{type:"callout",variant:"tip",content:'When an adjective comes before the noun and the noun has a definite article, the adjective takes the article instead: "frumoasa grădină" (the beautiful garden). This is rare at A1 level, but good to recognize.'}]},{id:"practice-agreement",title:"Matching Adjectives to Nouns",blocks:[{type:"text",content:"Here is a practical summary. When you want to describe a noun, ask: (1) What is the gender? (2) Is it singular or plural? Then choose the correct adjective form."},{type:"table",headers:["Noun","Gender/Number","Adjective (bun)","Result"],rows:[["un băiat","masc. sg.","bun","un băiat bun (a good boy)"],["o fată","fem. sg.","bună","o fată bună (a good girl)"],["niște băieți","masc. pl.","buni","niște băieți buni (some good boys)"],["niște fete","fem. pl.","bune","niște fete bune (some good girls)"],["un scaun","neuter sg.","bun","un scaun bun (a good chair)"],["niște scaune","neuter pl.","bune","niște scaune bune (some good chairs)"]],caption:'The adjective "bun" (good) agreeing with different nouns',colorCoded:!0},{type:"callout",variant:"tip",content:"Remember: neuter singular = masculine adjective form, neuter plural = feminine adjective form. So you really only need to learn four forms: masculine singular, feminine singular, masculine plural, feminine plural."}]}]};export{e as default};
